\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(6+239k)^{717} &= \sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}\sum_{j=0}^{717}\binom{717}{j}6^{717-j}(239k)^j \\
&= \sum_{j=0}^{717}\binom{717}{j}6^{717-j}\sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(239k)^j
\end{align*}

**Step 2: Evaluate the inner summation**

The inner summation is a binomial expansion of $(1-239)^{717}$:

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(239k)^j &= (-239)^j\sum_{k=0}^{717}\binom{717}{k}(-1)^k k^j \\
&= (-239)^j(1-239)^{717} \cdot \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if } j = 0 \\ 0 & \text{if } j > 0 \end{cases}
\end{align*}

**Step 3: Simplify the expression**

Now, we can simplify the original expression:

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(6+239k)^{717} &= \sum_{j=0}^{717}\binom{717}{j}6^{717-j}(-239)^j(1-239)^{717} \cdot \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if } j = 0 \\ 0 & \text{if } j > 0 \end{cases} \\
&= \binom{717}{0}6^{717}(1-239)^{717} \\
&= (6-239)^{717} \\
&= (-233)^{717}
\end{align*}

**Step 4: Find the largest power of 2 that divides the result**

Since $233 \equiv 1 \pmod 4$, we know that $(-233)^{717} \equiv (-1)^{717} \equiv -1 \pmod 4$. Therefore, the largest power of 2 that divides $(-233)^{717}$ is $2^0 = 1$.

